Background

In the data folder, you will find data about shark incidents in California between 1950-2022. The data are from: State of California- Shark Incident Database.

Load the libraries

library("tidyverse")
library("janitor")

Load the data

Run the following code chunk to import the data. In this chunk, I am removing NAs.

sharks <- 
  read_csv("data/SharkIncidents_1950_2022_220302.csv", 
           na=c("NA", "N/A", "Unknown", "NOT COUNTED", "", " ")) %>% 
  clean_names()

  1. Are there any hotspots for shark incidents in California? Show the top five counties with the most incidents.
sharks %>%
  select(county) %>%
    group_by(county) %>%
  count(county) %>%
  summarize(across(where(is.numeric), ~sum(.x, na.rm=T))) %>%
  arrange(desc(n)) %>%
   slice_head(n=5)
## # A tibble: 5  2
##   county            n
##   <chr>         <int>
## 1 San Diego        25
## 2 Humboldt         20
## 3 San Mateo        19
## 4 Santa Barbara    19
## 5 Marin            16

The top 5 counties/hotspots with the most incidents are San Diego, Humboldt, San Mateo, Santa Barbara, and Marin county.

  1. Make a plot that shows the total number of incidents per county.
sharks %>%
ggplot(aes(x=county)) +
  geom_bar()+
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title="Total Number of Incidents by County", x="County", y = "Number of Incidents") +
    theme(plot.title=element_text(size=rel(1.5), hjust = 0.5))

  1. Are there months of the year when incidents are more likely to occur? Make a plot that shows the total number of incidents by month. Which month has the highest number of incidents?
sharks %>%
ggplot(aes(x= as.factor(month))) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill= as.factor(month)))+
  labs(title="Total Number of Shark Incidents by Month", x="Month", y = "Number of Incidents", fill = "Month") +
  theme(plot.title=element_text(size=rel(1.5), hjust = 0.5)) +
  scale_y_log10()

Month 10 has the highest number of shark attack incidents, so the month of October. Incidents are more likely to occur around month 7 to month 10, so around July to October.

  1. Is there a time of day when most attacks occur? Make a plot that shows the total number of incidents by time of day. Which time of day has the highest number of incidents?
sharks %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=time)) +
  geom_bar(na.rm = T)+
  labs(title = "Shark Incidents by Time of Day", x = "Time of Day", y = "Number of Incidents") +
  theme(plot.title=element_text(size=rel(1.5), hjust = 0.5)) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=60, hjust = 1))

11:00 A.M. is the time of day with the highest number of incidents.

  1. How do the number and types of injuries compare by county? Make a table that shows the number of injury types by county. Which county has the highest number incidents? (hint: your table should be in wide format)
injury_table <- sharks %>%
  count(county, injury) %>%
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = injury,
    values_from = n,
    values_fill = 0
  )

  1. Use the table from #5 to make a plot that shows the total number of incidents by county.
injury_table %>%
  mutate(total_incidents = minor + `none` + major + `minor*` + `none*` + fatal + `major*`) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=county, y = total_incidents)) +
  geom_col(fill = "deeppink3", na.rm = T) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Total Shark Incidents by County", x = "County", y = "Total Incidents")+
   theme(plot.title=element_text(size=rel(1.5), hjust = 0.5))

  1. In the data, mode refers to a type of activity. Which activity is associated with the highest number of incidents?
sharks %>%
  count(mode, sort = T) %>%
  slice_head(n=1)
## # A tibble: 1  2
##   mode                   n
##   <chr>              <int>
## 1 Surfing / Boarding    85

Surfing/Boarding is associated with the highest number of incidents.

  1. Make a plot that compares the number of incidents by activity.
activity_counts <- sharks %>%
  group_by(mode) %>%
  summarize(total_incidents = n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = mode, y = total_incidents)) +
  geom_col(aes(fill=mode)) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Shark Incidents by Activity", x = "Activity", y = "Number of Incidents") +
  theme(plot.title=element_text(size=rel(1.5), hjust = 0.5))
activity_counts

  1. Are all incidents involving Great Whites fatal? Make a plot that shows the number and types of incidents for Great Whites only.
great_white <- sharks %>%
  filter(species == "White") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=injury)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill = injury)) +
  labs(title = "Incident Outcomes for Great White Sharks", x = "Injury Type", y = "Number of Incidents") +
  theme(plot.title=element_text(size=rel(1.5), hjust = 0.5))
great_white

No, not all incidents are fatal. They are mostly major, or even no injuries.
